properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A potent winter storm will impact southern Kivalliq on Sunday. This storm will bring strong northwesterly winds with gusts up to 80 km/h. These strong winds will lead to significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow, creating blizzard conditions. These winds will gradually diminish on Monday afternoon and visibilities will improve. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A potent winter storm will impact southern Baffin Island beginning late Saturday afternoon. The storm will bring significant winds, with gusts in excess of 90 km/h possible. This system will also bring 10 to 20 cm of snow. These winds combined with the falling snow will lead to significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow, creating near blizzard conditions for Iqaluit. Conditions will gradually improve Sunday evening. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A potent winter storm is set to impact Baffin Island later today and through to Monday. This weather system will bring the potential for wind gusts in excess of 90 km/h to Pangnirtung beginning early Sunday morning and persisting through the day. Winds will gradually diminish Sunday evening. Some snow is forecast with this system as well, which combined with the strong winds will create reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Confidence is relatively high that these significant wind gusts will materialize, but there is still some uncertainty in regards to the track of the system, so this warning may be adjusted as the system approaches. Please stay alert for updated bulletins. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Local snow squalls today. An intense snow squall over Lake Erie will impact areas near Fort Erie late this morning and early this afternoon before drifting southward back over the lake late this afternoon. Wind gusts up to 70 km/h will result in local blowing snow, particularly over exposed areas. Hazards: Local snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm by this afternoon. Quickly accumulating snow of up to 5 cm per hour at times. Poor visibility in heavy snow and blowing snow. Impacts: Travel is likely to be hazardous. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Windy conditions for today. Maximum wind gusts: 70 to 80 km/h over exposed areas. Location: all of Nova Scotia. Time span: until this evening. Remarks: In addition to gusty winds, rain will develop across the rest of the province. Heavy rain continues for southwestern Nova Scotia and parts of Cumberland County where warnings are in effect. Later today, rain will switch to snow for some areas as the temperature drops. Locally snowfall amounts of 5 cm are possible, especially over higher terrain. Conditions will improve tonight. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
